The linework was symbolized using the COASTBND attribute and visually inspected. Accuracy was estimated at approaching 100% in May 2000.
In November 2003, a new attribute 'SUBCOAST' was created as an integer field and subtyped into three categories, 1 = internal boundary, 2 = coast, and 3 = state boundary. This attribute was populated with the existing attribute 'COASTBND'. For category 1, the default for 'COASTBND' was defined as 'B'; for category 2, it was defined as 'C'; and for category 3, it was defined as 'S'. It was then used to validate the 'COASTBND' attribute. Errors, if any, were corrected in ArcMap 8.3. The attribute was then deleted after use. A domain called dCOASTBND was also created for the attribute 'COASTBND' that was used to check attribute validity.
The final product was checked against the source material. The Mapping and GIS section of the Southwest Florida Water Management District corrected any errors found. There are no significant omissions.
Accuracy should meet accuracy standards for a 1:2,000,000 scale map, +/- 1000 meters.
In November 2003, all of the state boundary feature classes were positionally validated against the Florida Boundary feature class in a separate and temporary feature dataset. All of the feature classses had an attribute added, 'SUBCOAST', as an integer field which was used to subtype the boundary. This attribute was populated with the existing attribute 'COASTBND'. The subtyping allowed to only validate the coast line and not the interior boundaries. The subtype was grouped into three categories, 1 = internal boundary, 2 = coast, and 3 = state boundary. The Cluster Tolerance was defined to be 0.005 meters. The Topology Rules used for this validation was as follows: Florida Boundary lines must not self-overlap. State County boundary lines must not self-overlap. State County boundary lines: coast, must be covered by feature class of Florida Boundary lines: coast. State County boundary lines: state boundary, must be covered by feature class of Florida Boundary lines: state boundary. Any errors that were found were inspected and corrected using ArcMap 8.3. The subtype attribute was deleted after use.
In December 2003, the following Topolgy Rules were created and validated for the feature classes in the State County feature dataset: State County region must not overlap. State County region must be covered by State County boundary lines. The Cluster Tolerance was set at 0.005 meters. Any errors that were found were inspected and corrected using ArcMap 8.3.

The UNIX compressed file was downloaded from the DEP ftp site. The file was uncompressed using the UNIX uncompress command. The export file was imported using the ArcInfo IMPORT command. The fuzzy tolerance was set to .001 and polygon topology was created using the BUILD command. The coverage was projected from ALBERS to UTM using the PROJECT command with the projection parameters listed below. The BUILD command was then used to recreate polygon and create arc topology. The ArcInfo commands ADDITEM and DROPITEM were used to modify the polygon attribute table (PAT) and arc attribute table (AAT). The following items were added to the PAT: COUNTY, CNTYNAME, DATESTAMP. The following items were dropped from the PAT: MAJOR1, MINOR1, MAJOR2, MINOR2, NAME. The following items were added to the AAT: COASTBND, DATESTAMP. The REGIONDISSOLVE command was used to create a region subclass called COUNTY.
